\"hello, rhino:7\");\n            } finally {\n                Context.exit();\n            }\n        });\n    }\n\n    @Test\n    void serializesAndRestoresAdapterWrapper() throws Exception {\n        runAllowingNativeImageUnsupportedClassGeneration(() -> {\n            Context context = ContextFactory.getGlobal().enterContext();\n            context.setOptimizationLevel(-1);\n            try {\n                Scriptable scope = context.initStandardObjects();\n                Scriptable adapter = (Scriptable) context.evaluateString(scope, \"\"\"\n                        new JavaAdapter(java.lang.Runnable, {\n                            count: 0,\n                            run: function() {\n                                this.count = this.count + 1;\n                            },\n                            value: function() {\n                                return this.count;\n                            }\n                        });\n                        \"\"\", \"java-adapter-serialize\", 1, null);\n\n                ByteArrayOutputStream buffer = new ByteArrayOutputStream();\n                try (ScriptableOutputStream output = new ScriptableOutputStream(buffer, scope)) {\n                    output.writeObject(adapter);\n                }\n\n                Object restored;\n                try (ScriptableInputStream input = new ScriptableInputStream(\n                        new ByteArrayInputStream(buffer.toByteArray()),\n                        scope\n                )) {\n                    restored = input.readObject();\n                }\n\n                ScriptableObject.putProperty(scope, \"adapter\", restored);\n                Object result = context.evaluateString(scope, \"\"\"\n                        adapter.run();\n                        adapter.run();\n                        adapter.value();\n                        \"\"\", \"java-adapter-restored\", 1, null);\n\n                assertThat(Context.toNumber(result)).isEqualTo(2.0d);\n            } finally {\n                Context.exit();\n            }\n        });\n    }\n\n    @FunctionalInterface\n    private interface ThrowingRunnable {\n        void run() throws Exception;\n    }\n\n    private static void runAllowingNativeImageUnsupportedClassGeneration(ThrowingRunnable action) throws Exception {\n        try {\n            action.run();\n        } catch (Error error) {\n            if (!NativeImageSupport.isUnsupportedFeatureError(error)) {\n                throw error;\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    public static class ComparableGreeter implements Comparable<Object> {\n        public String greet(String name) {\n            return \"base \" + name;\n        }\n\n        @Override\n        public int compareTo(Object other) {\n            return 7;\n        }\n    }\n}\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1777676220036}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Tackling test interference**\n\nI need to address an issue with our test where the global SecurityController is initialized once in Main.main, which can cause side effects for other tests. I might need to avoid running tests that interact with it or find a way to isolate them, possibly by forking. Running in a separate Java process could help ensure the tests are counted properly, but I’m concerned about coverage. Managing the method order might help, but I’ll have to be careful about dependencies.\n\n**Exploring test isolation options**\n\nI'm trying to find a solution for resetting the SecurityController in my tests. Using reflection isn't appropriate since the rule says not to invoke it directly unless necessary. Setting a system property for a single JVM doesn't seem to work either. I thought about calling Main.main with a property, but I need to undo the securityImpl along with the global settings. Perhaps I could dynamically load Rhino Main using a custom ClassLoader to keep it separate from the system classes and avoid contamination. However, I need to ensure coverage with JaCoCo, which complicates things.\n\n**Considering classloader and main invocation**\n\nI’m weighing the options for loading jars with a custom classloader. If it loads the same jar, I might need to call Main.main reflectively, but there’s that rule against direct reflection unless it’s necessary for a public API. Invoking main would also likely require reflection. Instrumentation might track coverage, but it feels complicated. Instead, I wonder if using ProcessBuilder to create a Java subprocess would be simpler. Another idea is calling the org.mozilla.javascript.tools.shell.Main.main in the test and cleaning up afterward through serialization.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_08bba07ddcad8f7f0169f52facfbf88196b69aa4cc228e8edc\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAA